Q - Pod in CrashLoopBackOff
If a pod is in CrashLoopBackOff, I would first check the pod events using kubectl describe pod to understand why it is restarting. Then I would check logs using kubectl logs and also --previous
logs to capture the last failed execution. I would look for application errors like exceptions or missing dependencies. I would also check if the pod was OOMKilled due to memory limits or if
there is CPU throttling. Additionally, I would verify configuration issues like environment variables, ConfigMaps, or incorrect image versions

Q - Pod in Pending state
Ans - If a pod is in Pending state, I would first check scheduling events using kubectl describe pod to see why it is not assigned to a node. Common reasons include insufficient CPU or memory, 
node not ready, or taints preventing scheduling. I would also check if cluster autoscaler is working, as pods may be waiting for new nodes. Additionally, I would verify node affinity, 
pod constraints, and storage issues such as EBS volume AZ mismatch or unbound PVC

Q - 3. Service not reachable internally
I would first check if the service selector correctly matches pod labels. 
Then verify endpoints to ensure pods are registered. I would also check service ports and pod health. If everything looks correct, 
I would investigate network policies or kube-proxy issues

Q - Service not reachable externally
For external access, I would check if the service is of type LoadBalancer or if ingress is configured correctly. Then I would verify that the load balancer has a valid external IP and 
health checks are passing. 
I would also check security groups and ensure traffic is allowed. Finally, I would confirm that the service is correctly routing traffic to healthy pods

5. Pods restarting frequently
f pods are restarting frequently, I would first check kubectl describe pod to see restart reasons such as OOMKilled or probe failures.
Then I would check logs for application errors. Common causes include insufficient memory, failing liveness probes, configuration issues, or dependency failures.
Based on the root cause, I would adjust resource limits, fix application errors, or correct configurations

Q - 6. CPU low but latency high

If CPU is low but latency is high, it usually indicates an I/O or dependency bottleneck rather than compute. I would first check if the application is waiting on external services like databases,
APIs, or storage. Then I would investigate thread pool or connection pool exhaustion, where requests are waiting despite low CPU usage. 
I would also check network latency, DNS issues, and load distribution across pods. The goal is to identify where the system is blocked rather than busy.”

7. HPA not scaling

If HPA is not scaling, I would first check HPA status using kubectl describe hpa to see current vs target metrics. 
Then I would verify if metrics server is running, as HPA depends on metrics. I would also check if CPU requests are defined correctly and whether 
the current usage exceeds the threshold. Additionally, I would verify max replica limits and ensure the cluster has enough capacity to scale.
Finally, I would confirm that HPA is correctly linked to the target deployment

